<div id="review_36427020" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/36427020" />
    <a title="Ellen" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/904862-ellen"><img alt="Ellen" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1219800402p2/904862.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/36427020?book_show_action=true">Oct 28, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ellen" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ellen" href="/user/show/904862-ellen">Ellen</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/904862-ellen?shelf=food-and-cooking">food-and-cooking</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer36427020" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2632467688927401617">I should love this book. This should be the first book I go to when I need to make bread. I mean, its the freaking <i>Bread Bible</i>. But it&apos;s not. Beranbaum takes all the fun out of making bread with her teaspoon level measurements, lectures about proper flours, and rants about flavor development. <br/><br/>I get it. Bread is a science to Beranbaum. And to someone who feels the same way (which is probably most other bread bakers out there), I&apos;m sure this book is the Bible. But to me, bread baking is an art. Ok</span>
  <span id="freeText2632467688927401617" style="display:none">I should love this book. This should be the first book I go to when I need to make bread. I mean, its the freaking <i>Bread Bible</i>. But it's not. Beranbaum takes all the fun out of making bread with her teaspoon level measurements, lectures about proper flours, and rants about flavor development. <br /><br />I get it. Bread is a science to Beranbaum. And to someone who feels the same way (which is probably most other bread bakers out there), I'm sure this book is the Bible. But to me, bread baking is an art. Okay it's kind of like a three-year old with fingerpaints, but you get my drift.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2632467688927401617" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


