<div id="review_818036637" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/818036637" />
    <a title="Dick Wexelblat" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/24287683-dick-wexelblat"><img alt="Dick Wexelblat" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/818036637?book_show_action=true">Jan 09, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Dick Wexelblat" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Dick Wexelblat" href="/user/show/24287683-dick-wexelblat">Dick Wexelblat</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer818036637" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18214565732272491827">This is a superlative book for bread-making. No two ways about it. She gives clear detailed instructions with measurements in English volume and weight and metric weight. Most recipes have prep instructions for hand kneading, bread-hook kneading and bread-machine kneading.<br/><br/>B*U*T two caveats:<br/><br/>1) This book is extremely poorly proof-read and there are errors galore. Some are irrelevant, some will spoil the product, and some will just confuse the reader (such as telling you to add an ingredient not in</span>
  <span id="freeText18214565732272491827" style="display:none">This is a superlative book for bread-making. No two ways about it. She gives clear detailed instructions with measurements in English volume and weight and metric weight. Most recipes have prep instructions for hand kneading, bread-hook kneading and bread-machine kneading.<br /><br />B*U*T two caveats:<br /><br />1) This book is extremely poorly proof-read and there are errors galore. Some are irrelevant, some will spoil the product, and some will just confuse the reader (such as telling you to add an ingredient not in the mats list). I found such errors in the first two recipes I tried: Jewish rye and pumpernickel. So definitely, before beginning a recipe go to the author's web site and check out the errata list.<br /><br />2) These are pretty much all artisan recipes and will probably require things like overnight fermentation and up to three risings, and baking in enclosed containers. So if you're compulsive (like me) jump right in and take your time to make great bread.<br /><br />But if you're just getting started or don't have the time for an overnight prep, go to the King Arthur Flour website and check out the recipes section. Search on easy bread or quick bread or no-kneading bread. (Their No-knead Harvest Bread is fantastic. I make it several times a month.) I made KA's rye and bagels several times before graduating to Bread Bible's version.<br /><br />By the way, whatever recipe you use, you'll get best results by weighing the flour rather than measuring it in a cup. And use fresh yeast. Even if not expired, toss anything over a few months old unless you refrigerated it.</span>
  <a data-text-id="18214565732272491827" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


