<div id="review_3599727551" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3599727551" />
    <a title="Midori Feldman" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/123079294-midori-feldman"><img alt="Midori Feldman" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3599727551?book_show_action=true">Oct 17, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Midori Feldman" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Midori Feldman" href="/user/show/123079294-midori-feldman">Midori Feldman</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3599727551" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8396761073460772169">Confusing and needs major editing! How is it possible to write for pages and pages about soft starter, ending with a bit about stiff starter, and then only provide recipes using stiff starter? Why would the author say, “business letter turn” without an explanation of what that means? I had to find out from the internet that it doesn’t mean a turn at all, but a kind of fold. Now there may be some of you out there that want to defend this author, and tell me where I should have found that definiti</span>
  <span id="freeText8396761073460772169" style="display:none">Confusing and needs major editing! How is it possible to write for pages and pages about soft starter, ending with a bit about stiff starter, and then only provide recipes using stiff starter? Why would the author say, “business letter turn” without an explanation of what that means? I had to find out from the internet that it doesn’t mean a turn at all, but a kind of fold. Now there may be some of you out there that want to defend this author, and tell me where I should have found that definition in the book. But please, it should have been apparent from where I was reading the phrase. One shouldn’t have to read all the preceding 400+ pages to figure this out. I’m returning this book. It is for the birds, and I don’t mean manna from heaven.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8396761073460772169" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

